{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504582"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:17:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:17:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2343"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2343","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2343"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.48,0.35,0.09,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2343"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78851"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2343","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2343"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2343"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64200"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"152"},{"type":"tags","id":"2967"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1285"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1290"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1467"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27045"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33420"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78851","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78851"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day history of urinary frequency and dysuria. Her urine has become foul-smelling and dark brown in colour. She has no fever, flank pain, or systemic symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has a medical history of early-onset rheumatoid arthritis and was recently started on methotrexate. She develops a severe rash with ampicillin. She has no other known allergies or drug reactions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 120/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is mild suprapubic tenderness but no renal angle tenderness. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrinalysis shows protein ++, leucocytes +++, and nitrites +.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial antibiotic treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Flucloxacillin","Trimethoprim","Nitrofurantoin","Ciprofloxacin","Cefalexin"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms and urinalysis findings consistent with uncomplicated cystitis. The absence of fever, flank pain, and systemic symptoms makes pyelonephritis unlikely. Empirical antibiotic therapy should be initiated while awaiting urine culture results.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENitrofurantoin\u003C/strong\u003E is an appropriate first-line treatment for uncomplicated cystitis for nonpregnant women. It achieves high urinary concentrations and has good coverage against common uropathogens, including \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E. It is safe to use in patients taking methotrexate as there is no significant drug interaction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrimethoprim\u003C/strong\u003E would typically also be a reasonable first-line option in this setting. However, it is contraindicated in this patient due to concurrent methotrexate therapy, as the combination increases the risk of bone marrow suppression and folate deficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECiprofloxacin\u003C/strong\u003E should be reserved for more severe infections or based on culture sensitivities. Fluoroquinolones can increase methotrexate levels and the risk of toxicity. Additionally, there are concerns about antimicrobial resistance and side effects with fluoroquinolones.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlucloxacillin\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate as it lacks coverage against gram-negative organisms that typically cause urinary tract infections. Additionally, given the patient\u0027s history of severe rash with ampicillin, there is a risk of cross-reactivity with other beta-lactam antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECefalexin\u003C/strong\u003E is a reasonable alternative when first-line agents are contraindicated. While it provides adequate coverage for urinary tract pathogens, it has a broader spectrum than nitrofurantoin or trimethoprim and, therefore, is not first-line.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Nitrofurantoin and trimethoprim are first-line treatment options for uncomplicated cystitis in nonpregnant women","Trimethoprim should be avoided in patients taking methotrexate due to risk of bone marrow suppression","Cefalexin is a suitable alternative when first-line options are contraindicated, though broader spectrum"],"references":["Talan DA, Stamm WE, Hooton TM, et al. Comparison of ciprofloxacin (7 days) and trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole (14 days) for acute uncomplicated pyelonephritis pyelonephritis in women: a randomized trial. JAMA 2000; 283:1583.","Hooton TM. Clinical practice. Uncomplicated urinary tract infection. N Engl J Med 2012; 366:1028.","Warren JW, Abrutyn E, Hebel JR, et al. Guidelines for antimicrobial treatment of uncomplicated acute bacterial cystitis and acute pyelonephritis in women. Infectious Diseases Society of America (IDSA). Clin Infect Dis 1999; 29:745.","Antibiotic. In: Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; accessed {12 Jan 2025}. https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64200"}},"question":{"d